SIMPLE: proceed
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Proceed
<hw>Pro*ceed"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Proceeded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Proceeding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>proc⟦eacute⟧der</ets>. fr. L. <ets>procedere</ets>,
<ets>processum</ets>, to go before, to proceed; <ets>pro</ets> forward +
<ets>cedere</ets> to move. See <er>Cede</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
move, pass, or go forward or onward; to advance; to continue or renew
motion begun; <as>as, to <ex>proceed</ex> on a journey</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If thou <qex>proceed</qex> in this thy insolence.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pass from one point, topic, or stage, to another;
<as>as, to <ex>proceed</ex> with a story or argument</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To issue or come forth as from a source or origin;
to come from; <as>as, light <ex>proceeds</ex> from the
sun</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>proceeded</qex> forth and came from God.</q> <rj><qau>John
viii. 42.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It <qex>proceeds</qex> from policy, not love.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To go on in an orderly or regulated manner; to begin
and carry on a series of acts or measures; to act by method; to
prosecute a design.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that <qex>proceeds</qex> upon other principles in his
inquiry.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To be transacted; to take place; to occur.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He will, after his sour fashion, tell you⟦br⟧
What hath <qex>proceeded</qex> worthy note to-day.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To have application or effect; to operate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This rule only <qex>proceeds</qex> and takes place when a person
can not of common law condemn another by his sentence.</q>
<rj><qau>Ayliffe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To begin and carry on a legal
process.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To advance; go on; continue; progress; issue;
arise; emanate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proceed</ent>⟦br⟧

